# AI Dungeon Master — environment variables
# Copy to `.env` and fill in. Nothing is strictly required: with no API key the
# server runs an OFFLINE MOCK narrator so the full loop + UI work without
# secrets (the engine still produces every real number). Set LLM_API_KEY for
# full LLM narration. These are read by apps/server/src/config.ts and compose.
#
# IN-APP SETTINGS: the LLM provider/key/model, image generation, the campaign
# selection, and the SRD path can also be set from the web UI (gear icon, top
# right) — they are stored in <vault>/settings.json and OVERRIDE the values
# below. So you only strictly need a minimal bootstrap .env here (vault path,
# port/host, Piper URL, optional Basic Auth, Cloudflare token); everything else
# is optional and configurable in the GUI. Env stays the fallback/default.
# (LLM-applied live; campaign + SRD path apply on the next server start.)

# --- LLM (provider-agnostic, OpenAI-compatible; spec §9.1) -------------------
# CONFIGURE IN THE APP, NOT HERE (recommended). The LLM key/base-URL/model,
# image generation and Azure TTS are all set from the GUI and persisted in the
# vault (<vault>/settings.json), so they survive redeploys and override these
# env values. In a hosted/commercial deploy only an admin can change them, from
# the /admin panel → "Server" → Poskytovatelé; in self-hosted they're also in
# the gear Settings. The env vars below stay only as an OPTIONAL bootstrap floor
# (e.g. first-run before you log in as admin). Leave them empty to start on the
# offline mock narrator and fill everything in via the admin panel.
#
# API key for your LLM provider (Mistral, OpenRouter, etc.). If empty, the
# server uses the offline mock narrator. Set LLM_PROVIDER=mock to force it
# even when a key is present.
# LLM_API_KEY=
# LLM_PROVIDER=mock

# Base URL of the OpenAI-compatible chat-completions endpoint.
# Default: Mistral. Set to OpenRouter's base URL to route there instead.
# LLM_BASE_URL=https://api.mistral.ai/v1

# Model id (overridable per campaign via campaign.yaml).
# LLM_MODEL=mistral-medium-3.5

# --- Vault (file-first content + state; spec §6) -----------------------------
# Path to the vault root (contains campaigns/ and optionally srd/).
# Locally, point at the bundled example. In Docker this is /data/vault.
VAULT_PATH=./data/vault.example

# Optional: pick a specific campaign folder under <vault>/campaigns.
# If unset, the server uses the first campaign it finds.
# CAMPAIGN=konvoj-do-vresoviste

# Shared SRD dataset (5e-bits/5e-database JSON). Optional — defaults to the
# in-repo bundled copy (packages/srd/data, #45a), so the app works with no
# external dataset. Docker stages that copy at /data/srd. Set SRD_PATH only to
# point at your own database (env) or use the in-app "Cesta k SRD" setting; a
# Compose bind mount (./srd:/data/srd) overrides it too. The loader is tolerant
# of the 5e-database layout and of missing files (even a 3-file subset works).
# SRD_PATH=/data/srd

# --- TTS (Czech narration; spec §11) -----------------------------------------
# Azure TTS (key/region/voice) is GUI-managed too — set it in the admin panel /
# gear Settings; it persists in the vault and overrides the env. The Piper
# FALLBACK URL stays env-only (it's a bootstrap/infra address). The Azure env
# vars below are an optional bootstrap floor.
#
# Two engines, tried in order: Azure AI Speech (PRIMARY — expressive, dramatic
# Czech neural voices) then Piper (FALLBACK — local, flat but free/offline).
# Set neither to disable TTS entirely.
#
# Azure AI Speech (recommended for a vivid Pán-jeskyně voice):
#   1. Create a free "Speech" resource at https://portal.azure.com
#      (free tier F0 ≈ 500k characters/month). Copy a KEY and the REGION.
#   2. Fill these in. Czech voices: cs-CZ-AntoninNeural (m), cs-CZ-VlastaNeural (f).
# These are ALSO settable in the web UI (gear → Hlas), which overrides the env;
# so they are optional here. Region is e.g. westeurope.
# AZURE_SPEECH_KEY=
# AZURE_SPEECH_REGION=westeurope
# AZURE_TTS_VOICE=cs-CZ-AntoninNeural
# Drama tuning via SSML prosody (slower + lower reads as more gravitas):
# AZURE_TTS_RATE=-6%
# AZURE_TTS_PITCH=-2%
# Optional mstts express-as style (most cs-CZ voices ignore it; leave empty):
# AZURE_TTS_STYLE=
# Output format (RIFF/WAV the browser plays directly):
# AZURE_TTS_FORMAT=riff-24khz-16bit-mono-pcm
#
# Piper fallback — local HTTP endpoint (POST /tts {text} -> audio/wav).
# Used automatically if Azure is unset or errors. In Docker: http://piper:5000
# PIPER_URL=http://localhost:5000

# --- Image generation (on-demand portraits, locations, scene atmosphere) ------
# GUI-managed too: enable + set base URL / model / key in the admin panel / gear
# Settings (persisted in the vault, overrides env). The env vars below are an
# optional bootstrap floor.
# Set IMAGE_BASE_URL to enable. Leave unset to disable the feature entirely.
#
# Mistral (recommended — same key as LLM, uses Agents + image_generation tool):
#   IMAGE_BASE_URL=https://api.mistral.ai/v1
#   IMAGE_MODEL=mistral-medium-2505   ← default when base URL contains mistral.ai
#   IMAGE_API_KEY=                    ← falls back to LLM_API_KEY automatically
#
# OpenAI (DALL-E 3):
#   IMAGE_BASE_URL=https://api.openai.com/v1
#   IMAGE_MODEL=dall-e-3
#
# Together AI (FLUX, free tier available):
#   IMAGE_BASE_URL=https://api.together.xyz/v1
#   IMAGE_MODEL=black-forest-labs/FLUX.1-schnell-free
#
# IMAGE_BASE_URL=
# IMAGE_MODEL=
# IMAGE_API_KEY=

# --- Cloudflare Tunnel (alternative to Caddy; spec §14.3) -------------------
# Zero-config public HTTPS without exposing ports 80/443 on the NAS.
# Create a named tunnel at https://one.dash.cloudflare.com → Networks → Tunnels,
# choose "token-based", and copy the tunnel token here. Then set the public
# hostname in the Zero Trust dashboard to route to http://app:3000.
# Enable the cloudflared sidecar with:
#   docker compose --profile cloudflare up -d
# Caddy is opt-in too (--profile caddy); without a profile no ports are opened.
# CLOUDFLARE_TUNNEL_TOKEN=

# --- Server -------------------------------------------------------------------
# HTTP port and bind host.
# PORT=3000
# HOST=0.0.0.0

# Optional single shared HTTP Basic Auth gate, "user:pass". Empty = no auth
# (rely on Cloudflare Access / Tailscale / network isolation instead).
# Spec §13, §18.4. Strongly recommended if you expose the app publicly.
# NOTE: this is an operator-only lock that sits IN FRONT of everything. It is
# independent of the per-user accounts below; for a public commercial deploy you
# typically leave BASIC_AUTH empty and rely on the account system instead.
# BASIC_AUTH=

# Path to the built web client. Defaults to apps/web/dist relative to the
# server build; the Docker image sets this to /app/apps/web/dist.
# WEB_DIST=

# --- Accounts / authentication (#55–58) --------------------------------------
# The app ships a full email account system: registration, email verification,
# login with server-side sessions (httpOnly cookie), password reset, an admin
# panel (/admin) and per-user data isolation. It runs in two modes:
#
#   * SELF-HOSTED (default): AUTH_ALLOW_ANONYMOUS=true → a "continue without
#     login" button is shown, everyone shares one vault, accounts are optional.
#   * HOSTED / COMMERCIAL: AUTH_ALLOW_ANONYMOUS=false → login is required and
#     every user gets isolated data under <vault>/users/<id>/.
#
# User data (accounts, sessions, credits, audit log) lives in an SQLite file at
# <vault>/db/app.db — keep the vault on a persistent volume so it survives
# redeploys (Docker: the named vault_data volume already does this).
#
# --- COMMERCIAL DEPLOY: a minimal working set is marked [COMMERCIAL] below. ---

# Require login; turn OFF anonymous access. [COMMERCIAL: false]
# AUTH_ALLOW_ANONYMOUS=false

# Allow self-service sign-up. Set false to run an invite/admin-only instance.
# AUTH_REGISTRATION=true

# Require a verified email before login is allowed. Keep true in production so
# sign-ups must confirm their address (needs working email, see SMTP below).
# AUTH_REQUIRE_VERIFIED=true

# Email that is granted the admin role (panel at /admin). The account is
# promoted on startup and when it registers. Set this to YOUR email, register
# with it first, and you become admin. [COMMERCIAL: your-admin@example.com]
# ADMIN_EMAIL=

# Brute-force throttles for the credential endpoints (#59b), per client IP.
# MAX attempts are allowed per WINDOW_MS; further attempts get HTTP 429 with a
# Retry-After header. A successful login clears that IP's login counter. Set a
# MAX to 0 to disable that limit. Defaults: login 10 / 15 min, register 5 / 1 h.
# AUTH_LOGIN_RATE_MAX=10
# AUTH_LOGIN_RATE_WINDOW_MS=900000
# AUTH_REGISTER_RATE_MAX=5
# AUTH_REGISTER_RATE_WINDOW_MS=3600000

# Public base URL of this server (NO trailing slash). Used to build the links
# inside verification / password-reset emails — MUST be the real external URL
# or those links will point at localhost. [COMMERCIAL: https://your-domain]
# PUBLIC_URL=https://dm.example.com

# Secret used to sign verification / reset / session tokens (HMAC). If unset a
# random secret is generated and persisted to <vault>/db/auth-secret. For a
# multi-instance / reproducible deploy, set a long random value explicitly so
# tokens stay valid across instances and re-creates. [COMMERCIAL: set this]
#   generate e.g.:  openssl rand -base64 48
# AUTH_SECRET=

# --- Outbound email (SMTP) — required for verification & password reset -------
# Without SMTP_HOST the server does NOT send mail; it only LOGS the verification
# / reset links to the server console (fine for dev, not for production). For a
# commercial deploy point this at a real provider (Resend/SES/Mailgun/SMTP).
# [COMMERCIAL: configure all of these]
# SMTP_HOST=smtp.example.com
# SMTP_PORT=587
# SMTP_SECURE=false          # true for implicit TLS (port 465)
# SMTP_USER=
# SMTP_PASS=
# SMTP_FROM=no-reply@example.com

# --- Credits / metering (#56) — monetisation ---------------------------------
# Off by default so self-hosted / BYO-key runs are never charged. Turn on to
# meter usage against per-user credit balances; players are blocked (HTTP 402)
# when their balance hits zero. Admins grant credits from the /admin panel.
# A real payment gateway (Stripe) is not wired up yet — top-ups are admin-driven
# for now. Prices are integer credits (smallest unit, no floats). [COMMERCIAL:
# enable + price so cost-of-tokens + markup is covered.]
# CREDITS_ENABLED=true

# Flat price charged per player turn (one LLM message). Per-model overrides are
# set in the admin panel; this is the fallback.
# CREDITS_PER_MESSAGE=10
# Flat price to forge/generate a campaign.
# CREDITS_PER_CAMPAIGN=200
# Flat price per generated image.
# CREDITS_PER_IMAGE=50
# Price per 1000 characters of TTS narration.
# CREDITS_PER_1K_TTS_CHARS=2
# Token cost-basis (logged per turn for reporting; not charged directly while
# billing is per-message above).
# CREDITS_PER_1K_PROMPT=1
# CREDITS_PER_1K_COMPLETION=3

# --- Hardening reminders before going public (ROADMAP #59) -------------------
# The account/credit surface is functional but a few hardening items are still
# open: login & registration are rate-limited (#59b, see AUTH_*_RATE_* above),
# state-changing /api routes require a custom header against CSRF (#59a), and
# self-service account deletion purges the user's vault subtree for GDPR (#59e).
# Still missing: a CAPTCHA, and a data export on deletion. Until then, keep the
# app behind a proxy/WAF and keep ADMIN_EMAIL tightly held.
